      <hedline>
        <hl1>Omen for Freetown</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Monica Edinger letter on June 26 article recalls life in Freetown, Sierra Leone</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I was one of the hundreds of Peace Corps volunteers who whiled away many an hour on the second-floor veranda of the City Hotel in Freetown, Sierra Leone (Freetown Journal, June 26), drinking Star beer and taking in the Graham Greene-like colonial atmosphere while watching the late-afternoon flight of the bats out of the palm trees along the street.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I was one of the hundreds of Peace Corps volunteers who whiled away many an hour on the second-floor veranda of the City Hotel in Freetown, Sierra Leone (Freetown Journal, June 26), drinking Star beer and taking in the Graham Greene-like colonial atmosphere while watching the late-afternoon flight of the bats out of the palm trees along the street.</p>
        <p>While the City Hotel may be in ruins, the huge old tree known as the Cotton Tree still stands in Freetown, a hopeful omen that this raked-over country badly needs.</p>
        <p>MONICA EDINGER  New York, June 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
